article.headline: Iowa State 68, Oklahoma State 52
article.story: AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Iowa State's four-game losing streak is over. So is Rahshon Clark's slump. Clark had his best game in almost three weeks with 19 points, Curtis Stinson added 18 and Iowa State beat Oklahoma State 68-52 on Wednesday night. "We finally got the monkey off our backs," Iowa State's Will Blalock said. "We're ready to pick it up now." Oklahoma State (14-13, 4-9 Big 12) was coming off an 81-60 rout of then-No. 6 Texas, but never came close to matching the proficiency it showed in that game. The Cowboys were sloppy with the ball, shot poorly and went nearly nine minutes near the end of the first half without scoring. Much of that was due to Iowa State's aggressive half-court defense. Normally a team that plays a 2-3 zone, the Cyclones frustrated the Cowboys with a man-to-man for much of the second half. Stinson and his teammates also took the ball to the basket instead of settling for jump shots and built a 26-6 edge in points on turnovers. "Our defensive intensity is getting there," Stinson said. "Guys are figuring out what to do. We're getting steals like we normally do as Cyclones. That's our game." Iowa State had a big edge in two other key areas. The Cyclones shot more free throws (26-7) than their opponent for only the second time in a Big 12 game and outrebounded a conference opponent (41-32) for just the third time this season. "I'm going to have a cigar on that later," ISU coach Wayne Morgan said. Trailing by eight midway through the first half, Iowa State ran off 15 points during OSU's drought and finished the half with a 17-2 run to open a 31-24 lead. Oklahoma State never got closer than five in the second half. "You play good at home (against Texas), you come here and it's a different ballgame," said Mario Boggan, who led Oklahoma State with 17 points. "We need to go home and get a win." Clark had scored 24 points in Iowa State's last victory, against Colorado on Feb. 5. But he made just 12 of 29 shots during the losing streak. "We knew he was going to step it up," Blalock said. "He came up to me and Curtis and told us he was going to take some of the bricks off our shoulders. He made it a lot easier for me." Stinson shot 6-for-10 and complemented his scoring with nine rebounds, five assists and two steals. He sprained the ring finger on his right hand going for a rebound in the first half, but sat out less than four minutes. Stinson played with a hand injury each of the two previous seasons. "If he breaks his hand again, we're like ducks on the water on the first day of hunting," Morgan said. Byron Eaton added 12 points for Oklahoma State. JamesOn Curry, who had 22 against Texas, was held to eight on 3-for-12 shooting. The Cowboys shot 41.7 percent and finished with 24 turnovers. It was Oklahoma State's fourth game with assistant coach Sean Sutton running the team in place of his father. Eddie Sutton is on medical leave and facing a drunken driving charge from a traffic accident on Feb. 10. The university announced earlier Wednesday that Sutton would undergo surgery on Thursday to correct chronic hip and back problems. The Cowboys are 1-3 in his absence. "This is a disappointing setback," Sean Sutton said. "We still have confidence in our players, but we can't do the things that got us in trouble tonight. We didn't dig in and defend and we didn't rebound." Iowa State quickly built its lead to 35-24 in the second half, then answered every time the Cowboys threatened. When Oklahoma State drew to 45-40, Iowa State responded with an 11-2 run. Stinson brought the crowd to its feet near the end of that spurt when he fired a behind-the-back pass to Jiri Hubalek, then followed up for a basket when Hubalek missed his layup. Later, Stinson lobbed to Clark for a backboard-shaking dunk that made it 64-49.
